INFS3201/7202: Django Admin Panel (Optional Self-Paced Tutorial)

The Django admin panel is a built-in web interface that makes it easy to manage the data in your application. Once youâve defined your models, the admin panel lets you create, read, update, and delete (CRUD) entries for those modelsâwithout writing any extra views or forms.

All you need to do is register your models with the admin interface using a simple configuration in admin.py. Django takes care of the rest, generating a full-featured interface for your models, complete with search, filtering, and validation.

Important

â ï¸ The admin panel is not meant for your appâs end users. Itâs designed for developers, staff, or site administrators to manage content behind the scenes. If you need custom views or user-facing forms, youâll build those separately.

The admin panel is a powerful tool for quickly managing data during development and for backend content management in production (with proper access controls).

Recap on the Models Setup in Lab 3

In Lab 3 you added the following models in resumeapp/models.py. It is ok if you added a few more fields to the models by completing the challenge activity.

from django.contrib.auth.models import User
from django.db import models

class UserDetail(models.Model):
    user = models.OneToOneField(User, on_delete=models.CASCADE)  # Link to Django's built-in User model
    firstname = models.CharField(max_length=100)
    surname = models.CharField(max_length=100)
    mobileno = models.CharField(max_length=15, blank=True, null=True)

    def __str__(self):
        return f"Details for {self.user.username}"

class Qualification(models.Model):
    user = models.ForeignKey(UserDetail, on_delete=models.CASCADE)  # One user can have many qualifications
    title = models.CharField(max_length=200)
    university = models.CharField(max_length=200)
    date_completed = models.DateField()

    def __str__(self):
        return f"{self.title} from {self.university} (User: {self.user.user.username})"

class WorkExperience(models.Model):
    user = models.ForeignKey(UserDetail, on_delete=models.CASCADE)  # One user can have many jobs
    job_title = models.CharField(max_length=200)
    company = models.CharField(max_length=200)
    start_date = models.DateField()
    end_date = models.DateField(blank=True, null=True)  # Can be blank for current jobs
    description = models.TextField(blank=True, null=True)

    def __str__(self):
        return f"{self.job_title} at {self.company} (User: {self.user.user.username})"

Step 2: Additional Security Settings to Get the Admin Panel Working

CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery) is a security vulnerability where a malicious website tricks a logged-in user into submitting a request to your site without their knowledgeâlike posting a form or changing settings. Django protects against this by checking for a valid CSRF token on form submissions.

We need to do some additional config to get the Admin panel working.

Add the following line to your settings.py file:

CSRF_TRUSTED_ORIGINS = ["https://yourzoneid.uqcloud.net", "https://infs3202-yourzoneid.uqcloud.net"]

This setting tells Django to trust these specific domains when handling secure (HTTPS) POST requests. Without it, Django might block valid requestsâespecially in cloud-hosted environments like UQCloudâthinking theyâre potential CSRF attacks.

Step 3: Setting up Static Files

In Django, collectstatic is used to gather all static files (like CSS, JavaScript, and images) from your apps into a single directory so they can be served efficiently

Make a new folder in /var/www/htdocs/ called resumebuilder_static. You can do this using Linux commands (e.g. mkdir) or via VSCode Online.

Change the STATIC_URL = 'static/' to have the name of your app in the path (so that you can have multiple static files directories). Add the additional code to to set STATIC_ROOT:

STATIC_URL = 'resumebuilder_static/'

# The directory where collectstatic will place all static files
STATIC_ROOT = "/var/www/htdocs/resumebuilder_static/"  # Used in production

/var/www/htdocs/ is already set to serve static files in our nginx configuration. We can place Djangoâs static files in this path and all the files (css and js) will then be available via `https://infs3202-yourzoneid.uqcloud.net/resumebuilder_staticâ

Now run the collectstatic command to move all the stylesheets and js files for the Django Admin panel to a static files folder:

python3.12 manage.py collectstatic

You should see the following message:

127 static files copied to '/var/www/htdocs/resumebuilder_static/'

Step 4: Register Models in Django Admin

By default, Djangoâs admin panel already manages User accounts. We need to register our custom models to make them manageable from the admin interface.

Open resumeapp/admin.py and add the following code:

from django.contrib import admin
from .models import UserDetail, Qualification, WorkExperience

admin.site.register(UserDetail)
admin.site.register(Qualification)
admin.site.register(WorkExperience)

This tells Django which models should be visible in the admin panel.

Customising the Django Admin Panel

The Django admin panel can be easily customized to make data management easier. You can display specific columns, add search functionality, and enable filteringâall by configuring the ModelAdmin class in admin.py.

Letâs walk through an example using the UserDetail, Qualification, and WorkExperience models.

Step 1: Register Your Models

You can customize how each model appears in the admin panel by creating a custom ModelAdmin class. Hereâs how:


from django.contrib import admin
from .models import UserDetail, Qualification, WorkExperience

@admin.register(UserDetail)
class UserDetailAdmin(admin.ModelAdmin):
    list_display = ('user', 'firstname', 'surname', 'mobileno')  # Columns shown in the list view
    search_fields = ('firstname', 'surname', 'user__username')   # Enables search

@admin.register(Qualification)
class QualificationAdmin(admin.ModelAdmin):
    list_display = ('title', 'university', 'user', 'date_completed')
    search_fields = ('title', 'university', 'user__user__username')
    list_filter = ('university', 'date_completed')  # Adds filter sidebar

@admin.register(WorkExperience)
class WorkExperienceAdmin(admin.ModelAdmin):
    list_display = ('job_title', 'company', 'user', 'start_date', 'end_date')
    search_fields = ('job_title', 'company', 'user__user__username')
    list_filter = ('company', 'start_date')
Note

What does user__user__username mean?

In Django admin (and in query lookups), the __ (double underscore) syntax is used to follow relationships between models.

Letâs break down user__user__username step by step:

  • user: This refers to the user field on the Qualification or WorkExperience model, which is a ForeignKey to UserDetail.
  • user__user: From UserDetail, this follows the user field, which is a OneToOne link to Djangoâs built-in User model.
  • user__user__username: Finally, this gets the username field from the built-in User model.

So this is how you access the username of the Django User linked through two relationships:

Qualification â UserDetail â User â username

This syntax is commonly used in search_fields, filters, and queries to look up related fields across models.

What These Do?

  • list_display: Controls which fields are shown in the list view of the admin panel.
  • search_fields: Adds a search bar that lets you look up records based on these fields.
  • list_filter: Adds filters on the right-hand side to narrow down records by category or date.

With just a few lines of config, the admin panel becomes much more powerful and user-friendly for managing your appâs data.

Adding Custom Actions to the Admin Panel

In the Django admin panel, you can perform actions on multiple items at once. By default, the admin includes a âDelete selectedâ action that lets you bulk delete records.

But youâre not limited to just deletingâyou can create your own custom actions. For example, instead of deleting records, you might want to mark them as archived by setting a status or archived flag.
